{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060866A/1957120101/0023.xml":{"full_text":"ON THE RECORD\nThe Vice President\nStates His Views\nBy CECIL HOLLAND\nVice President Richard M.\nNixon once more has become the\nfocus of world-wide attention The\nlatest Illness of President Eisen\nhower, his third health crisis in\ntwo yews, has lifted Mr. Nixon\nfrom the traditional obscurity of\nhis office, which even his restless\nenergies and far-ranging Interests\ncould not wholly relieve.\nMr. Elsenhower's rapid recovery\nappears to have ruled out. at least\nfor the time being, any blanket\ndelegation of authority to Mr.\nNixon. But at the same time It\nseems likely that Mr. Nixon will\nhave an Increasingly Important\nvoice In the administration and its\ndecisions.\nThe Vice President, who will be\n45 years old on January 9, has\nbeen regarded In many quarters as\nMr. Elsenhower\u2019s heir appwent.\nand it was to him more than to\ncabinet leaders that the White\nHouse staff turned for advice and\nconsultation during the hours\nwhile Mr. Elsenhower's most re\ncent Illness was being evaluated.\nHe helped make one important\ndecision In which Mr. Elsenhower\ndid not participate\u2014the orders to\ngo ahead with both the Army's\nJupiter and the Air Force's Thor\nmissiles.\nMr. Nixon has been designated\nby Mr. Elsenhower to attend the\nimportant NATO Council meeting\nin Paris this month, if the Presi\ndent Is unable to attend. And\nhis advtee is being sought on\nmany other matters, including the\nbudget the administration must\nsubmit to Congress next month.\nThus Mr. Nixon s role already\nhas been enlarged, although he\ninsists that his position hasn't\nchanged and he Is \u201cJust helping\nout\u201d where he can. In view of his\nincreased activities, the question\nnaturally arises: Where does MV.\nNixon stand on the vital issues of\nthe day?\nIn recent months he has made\nhis position clear on almost every\nsubject confronting the Govern\nment in speeches, discussions and\nbackground remarks In fact, hia\nrecent statements on a wide va\nriety of subjects have prompted\nmany observers to decide that he\nis pursuing a more forthright and\nindependent course than he had\nbeen.\nIn whatever decisions he may\nparticipate, it seems certain from\nhis expressed views that he would\nundertake to further the over-all\npolicies of the Eisenhower admin\nistration and would supply some\nvigor which sometimes seems lack\ning in carrying them out.\nHere. In brief, are summarized\nviews expressed by Mr. Nixon in\nevent months on some of the\nissues confronting the country:\nBPCTXIKS AND MISSILES\nWhile the United States and its\nallies remain militarily stronger\nthan the Communist world. It\nwould be a serious mistake to\nbrush off the Soviet achievement\nin launching two satellites as \u2018a\nscientific stunt of more slgnficance\nto the man in the moon than to\nmen on esuth The Russian ac\ncomplishment, in Mr. Nixon s\nopinion Is significant in indicating\nthe Soviet ability to launch an\nintercontinental missile and the\nUnited States must hold Its own\nand never reach a position where\nthe Soviet Union could blackmail\nus or our allies. Hia views on this\nsubject soon after the announce\nment of Sputnik I were consider\nably stronger than those heard\nfrom other members of the admin\nistration.\nCOLD WAR The recent\nKhrushchev Manifesto is a warn\ning that the \"men In the Kremlin\nare launching right now a massive\nnonmilitary offensive aimed at\nthe overthrow of all free govern\nments\u201d and the United States must\nbe prepared \u201cfor patient en\ndurance of a cold war for an\nindefinite period.\u201d\nNATO AIXIANCE\u2014Despite the\ndifficulties with Great Britain and\nFrance in the Suez crisis \u201cour\nalliance with the NATO countries\nis stronger, militarily, economically\nand politically than it has\nbeen at any time since World\nWar n.\u201d\nDEFENSE SPENDING AND\nFOREIGN AID\u2014As long as the\nCommunist threat continues as\ngreat as It Is at the present, \u201cwe\nmust continue to maintain our\nmilitary strength at home and we\nmust continue to support our\nallies abroad\" and \u201cI see no time\nin the Immediate future when we\nare going to be able to get rid of\nthis burden.\u201d\nThe 93.4 billion In foreign aid\nvoted at the last session of 'Con\ngress Is \"a bare minimum\u201d and\n\u201can argument can be made for\nIncreasing It In some respects\nEconomic assistance Is \u201cthe most\nimportant part of the whole\nmutual security program\u201d and\na JBHBHI\nREPORTERS stuck close to Mr. Nixon while President Has laid up.\n\n\u201conly by shoring up the economies\nof the so-called neutral countries\ndo we keep the Communists out.\u201d\nRECIPROCAL TRADE AGREE\nMENTR\u2014The trade agreements\nact \"should be extended for at\nleast five years\" when it comes up\nin the next session of Congress.\nBUDGET AND TAXES Any\nreduction In the present S7O bil\nlion budget would have to be\nmade in expenditures for national\nsecurity and \u201cI do not anticipate\nin this next session that the Con\ngress is going to vote a $5 or\nbillion dollar cut ithe amount re\ngarded as necessary before there\ncould be a tax \u00abpt> If $4 billion\nhas to come out of national secu\nrity.\u201d\nLITTLE ROCK AND CtVIL\nRIGHTS President Elsenhower.\nIn Mr Nixon\u2019s Opinion, had no\nother choice but to send troops\nto Little Rock to enforce the\nschool integration orders of a Fed\neral court.\nThe President. Mr. Nixon be\nlieves. acted with full constitu\ntional authority and at the ap\npropriate moment to prevent vio\nlence and possible bloodshed on\nthe basis of reports he had from\nthe FBI and Little Rock citizens.\nMr. Nixon strongly disagrees\nwith the view that the President's\naction was a blow at the princi\nple of States\u2019 rights. In sending\ntroops to Little Rock, according to\nMr. Nixon, the President In the\nlong run was acting in the only\npossible way to maintain the prin\nciple of States\u2019 rights in the federal\nsystem and to avoid the chaos\nand disrespect for law and order\ngenerally that would result where\npeople with impunity blocked the\ncarrying out of a Federal court\norder.\nAs for solving the problem the\nVice President believes that cus\ntoms and attitudes cannot be\nchanged in a year or two. or five\nyears for that matter. But he be\nlieves the change must come out\nof moral and economic considera\ntions and the Impact such inci\ndents as Little Rock have Inter\nnationally. and that the solution\nmust be worked out eventually by\nmoderate Southern leaders.\nMr. Nixon was regarded as one\nof the supporters of a strong civil\nrights bill in the last session. The\nbill that was passed was confined\ntargelv to voting rights and looking\nback on that Mr. Nixon is now of\nthe opinion this was a moderate\nsolution to a difficult problem and\nperhaps the correct approach In\nsofar as what could be assimilated\nby the courts and people at this\ntime.\nLABOR LEGISLATION Con\ngress will consider and will likely\npass legislation to insure demo\ncratic processes In union elections,\nsafeguards for union finances and\npension and welfare funds and\npiwfidc bans on organizational\npicketing an\u00a3 secondary boycotts.\nHowever, t\u00bb Is Mr. Nixon's opin\nion that putting labor under the\nanti-trust law*, as proposed in\ntome quarters, would not correct\nabuses disclosed by the Senate\ncommittee investigating Improper\nlabor-management activities, and\nsuch legislation will not be a part\nof the administration's labor pro\ngram. Nor will the administration\nrecommend, according to Mr\nNixon, a national right-to-work\nlaw.\nFEDERAL AID TO EDUCATION\n\u2014There is at best a 50-50 chance\na school construction bill will pass\nthe House in the forthcoming\nsession but \"virtually no chance\u201d\nthat it will pass the Scute. At\nthe moment this legislation is \u201ca\ncasualty of the battle of the budg\net.\u201d Mr. Nixon believes a ma\nlority of Congress favors a bill\nlimited to construction and with a\nclear prohibition against any Fed\neral control of education. Even\nthis won't come, he believes, un\nless Congress becomes convinced\nthrough a stepped-up campaign\nstarting at the local level that the\nclassroom shortage Is so critical\nthat emergency Federal action la\n\u201cnot just desirable but urgently\nnecessary.\u201d\nMODERN REPUBLICANISM\u2014\nThe debate about \u201cmodern Repub\nlicanism.\u201d Mr. Nixon believes, has\nexaggerated the differences within\nthe Republican Party, and the\ndifference between a \u201cmodern Re\npublican\u201d and the traditional Re\npublican Is not so great that It\ncannot be reconciled enough so\nthat the party will present a\nunited front in the elections next\nyear and in 1960. The real split\nwithin the Republican Party, he\nfeels, is in the area of foreign\npolicy, but under the leadership\nof the Elsenhower administration\nthere has been a shift, with in\ncreasing support from those Re\npublicans who have In the past\nopposed reciprocal trade, mutual\nassistance and other International\nprograms.\nEditorials\nMusic-Radio-Books\nTHE WEEK IN PERSPECTIVE\nBroader Role for Mr. Nixon\n\u201cNo nan in the history of\nAmerica.\u201d President Elsenhower\nsaid on September 10. 1960, \"has\nhad such a careful preparation as\nVice President Nixon for carrying\nout the duties of the President.\u201d\nMr Nixon last week began a\nbrief demonstration of exactly how\nwell he has been trained for presi\ndential duties, whether shouldered\nIn a passing emergency\u2014ss at\npresent\u2014or taken on In actual\nsuccession to the presidency The\nreal significance of Mr. Eisen\nhower's latest illness could turn\nout to be the opportunity It has\ngiven Mr. Nixon to increase his\nparticipation in the highest coun\ncils of Government.\nWhen the President suffered a\nheart attack on September 24,\n1955. Mr Nixon assumed a much\nless significant role than he did\nlast week when Mr. Eisenhower\nwas stricken with a blockage In a\nbrain artery. In 1955 he partici\npated In some top-level decisions,\nbut It was he who remained in\nWashington while Sherman\nAdams, assistant to the President,\nstayed in Denver and spoke for\nMr. Elsenhower on policy matters.\nLast week when the President\nwas out of action the Vice Presi\ndent seemed to be much more\nactive in White House operation,\nand much leas was heard from Mr.\nAdams. During the anxious and\nconfusing hours after the onset\nof the occlusion In one of the\nPresident's small cerebral arteries,\nMr. Nixon was closer to the helm\nthan he has ever been before.\nHe put in an eight-hour day at\nthe White House on Tuesday. He\ntook a prominent role In some\nhigh-level decisions, including that\nwhich gave the go-ahead for pro\nduction of both the Thor and\nJupiter missiles. And for the first\ntime a Vice President held a\nscheduled press conference In the\nresidence of the President\u2014facing\nthe presidential seal on the wall\nof the office of the President's\npress secretary.\nOn Friday Mr. Nixon worked at\nthe White House with Mr. Adams,\nconferring on policy matters with\nAgriculture Secretary Ezra Ben\nson and Agriculture Department\naides. He also met briefly with\nMarion B. Folsom. Secretary of\nHealth. Education and Welfare.\nTomorrow he may preside at a\nmeeting of the cabinet, and on\nThursday he probably will present\nthe agenda of a National Security\nCouncil meeting. Mr. Eisenhower\nhas already chosen him ro repre\nsent the Nation at the December\n1$ meeting of the NATO council,\nshould the President be unable\nto attend himself. In this even\ntuality, Mr. Nixon could consider\nhimself \u201carrived\" In Die ranks of\nworld political leaders.\nThese Implications were plain:\nMr. Nixon, as active \u201cun\nderstudy\u201d to the President, had\nsuddenly come into a much larger\nshare of national policy-making\nthan he, or any other Vice Presi\ndent. has heretofore held.\nHis role in the direction of the\nadministration's legislative pro\ngrams will be greatly enlarged in\nthe congressional session begin\nning five weeks from tomorrow.\nHis influence on Republican\nParty policy will be strong, per*\nhaps even stronger than that of\nMr. Eisenhower, who has a natural\ntendency to shy from the purely\npolitical and 4rho. under the Con\nstitution. cannot be a candidate m\n1960.\nThe Illness\nMr. Eisenhower looked hale\nenough, considering his 67 years,\nas he waited in a chilly 45 de\ngrees at National Airport for the\narrival of a royal guest. King\nMohamed V of Morocco. The\nKing arrived almost exactly at\nnoon. Mr. Elsenhower welcomed\nhim. he received the key to the\ncity and a 21-gun salute was\nfired. Then the two chiefs of\nstate Inspected the Marine honor\nguard.\nThe drive to Blair House, the\nKing\u2019s home while he was here,\nwas made by the President, the\nKing and his son. Prince Moulay\nAbdullah, in the President\u2019s bub\nble-top sedan\u2014with the bubble\ntop down.\nThe President returned to the\nWhite House shortly after 1 p.m.\nand Immediately complained of a\nchill. He went to bed with an\nextra blanket and a hot-water\nbottle. At 2:40 p.m. he returned\nto his office, but within a few\nminutes he returned to his bed.\nHe was examined by six doctors\nat 3:45 pm., given mild sedation,\nand then went to sleep. The first\nword of the President's Illness\ncame at 6:20 pm., when it was\nannounced that he had gone to\nbed with a \u201cchill.\u201d\nThe President slept until 8 pm.\nwhen he awoke and had a light\nsupper In bed. Already an\nImpairment In his speech\u2014a diffi\nculty in pronunciation\u2014had be\ncome noticeable. He awoke again\nat 5 am. on Tuesday and was\nexamined by his doctors at 7:15\na.m.\nAt 8:53 am. Tuesday. White\nHouse reporters, who had become\nconcerned over the skimpy re\nports from the President's bed\nside, were told only that Mr.\nElsenhower was \u201cprogressing very\nwell.\u201d Mrs. Anne Wheaton, asso\nciate White House press secretary,\nacting in the absence of Press\nSecretary James Hagerty. refused\nto elaborate. Less than two hours\nlater Mrs. Wheaton met reporters\nagain, but she would say onlv that\nMr Eisenhower was \"progressing\nsatisfactorily.\u201d\nAt 3:15 p.m. the announcement\nthat shocked the world was made.\nThe President had suffered \"an\nocclusion of a small branch of\nthe middle cerebral artery on the\nleft side.\" This was 24 hours after\nthe doctors had made their first\nt\nWASHINGTON, D. C., DECEMBER i, 1957\nHBHIifIHHLSI \u25a0wmmmmmmrn uhhbb \u25a0\u25a0BHBHHHBBBHBHUHHBHHBBHBHBBP' *\u00a3sss&\nI i 9\u00bb\niTS Vi I\niff n iHi Bp mm\nI WS v a\n111 N#\n1 -TUm?\nkL kfey jml J m/ ,1\nBSBBkv\njgsy U H Mj\nVjSr wL\u25a0-\nv .Mijj\nLgf If\nJi* -v- I\nSEQUENCE \u2014On Tuesday the White House announced the true nature of the President's illness; on Thursday he attended church services.\nexamination. Mrs. Wheaton con\nceded that the physicians knew\nthen the true nature of the Pres\nident's ailment.\nThe White House doctors re\nfused to call the condition a\nstroke.\" although doctors not on\nthe case, including a National\nHeart Institute doctor and a past\npresident of the American Heart\nAssociation, said that the symp\ntoms clearly pointed to that. But\nfor the rest of the week Mr.\nEisenhower's doctors held to their\nposition.\nBy Wednesday morning Mr.\nEisenhower had shown a rapid\nimprovement in his condition. He\nbathed and shaved himself with\na safety razor. Mr. Hagerty. back\nfrom Europe, reported that his\nchief had laughed at his slight\nspeech impairment, which was re\nported to be improving rapidly.\nIn midmorning Mr. Elsenhower\nsigned 12 minor documents \u2019and\nconferred for 30 minutes with\nOen. Andrew J. Goodpaster, White\nHouse staff secretary.\nThe President\u2019s son, John, and\nhis brother. Milton, came for\nlunch, after which Mr. Eisenhower\nworked on an oil painting started\nsome time ago. While still at his\neasel he conferred with Mr. Nixon\nand Mr. Adams, retiring for a nap\nat 1:15 pm. He slept until after\n4 pm, and was awakened to meet\nSecretary of State Dulles and\nKing Mohamed. who had come to\ntell the President in general terms\nof some of the decisions that they\nhad reached in their discussions.\nMr. Eisenhower had an easy\nnight Wednesday, and on Thurs\nday attended Thanksgiving church\nservices with Mrs Eisenhower. On\nFriday he and Mrs. Eisenhower\nwere driven to their farm in Get\ntysburg. Pa, where the President\nwill rest and recuperate. Before\nleaving Washington, his personal\nphysician, MaJ. Gen. Howard M.\nSnyder, said that he was still\nmaking ''excellent\" progress to\nward recovery. This evaluation\nwas repeated yesterday in Gettys\nburg. Mr. Hagerty said he no\nlonger could detect any speech\ndifficulty.\nThe Reaction\nAlthough this was the least\nserious of the President's three\nmajor illnesses in the past 26\nmonths, it caused the same fre\nnetic concern that has come to\nmark every minor presidential\nache and pain.\nA major reason for the tremen-'\ndous attention given the Presi\ndent's health\u2014other than that it's\npresidential and that the President\nis a cardiac case\u2014no doubt de\nrives from a tendency to question\nWhite House reports on the sub\nject. Each of the three serious\nElsenhower illnesses has originally\nbeen represented as a minor\nailment.\nMr. Elsenhower's heart attack\nin 1955 was referred to for 12\nhours as a digestive upset despite\nthe fact that Dr Snyder, as he\nhas since testified, recognized it\nas a heart attack minutes after,\nreaching the President's bed\nside When Mr. 'Eisenhower suf\nfered an obstruction in the ileum\non June 8. 1956, it was 12 hours\nafter Dr. Snyder made his diag\nnosis before what had previously\nbeen called a stomach upset was\nrevealed as a condition serious\nenough to require immediate\nmajor surgery.\nAnd Monday\u2019s \"chill\" 24 hours\nlater became a cerebral occlusion\nserious enough to cause a speech\nimpediment.\nWhite House newsmen felt cer\ntain that if Mr. Hagerty had been\non hand, the truth would have\nbeen made public much sooner\nlast week. Mrs. Wheaton, inexperi\nenced in the delicate art of han\ndling persistent reporters, had\nbeen given the illusory medical\nbulletins and instructed to sa.v\nnothing further. Much of the\nblame for the hanging of the\nnews was laid to the ever-cautlous\nDr. Snyder and politically attuned\nMr Adams.\nAs a result, when the facts\nfinally did come out, a nervous\nand uncertain stock market re\nacted more sharply than it has\non the occasions of either of the\nother two major presidential ill\n-41\n\u00ael)c fsundms ffaf\nnesses. Leading stocks suffered\nlosses of $1 to $7 a share. The\nreassuring news of his rapid re\ncovery brought a quick rally,\nhowever.\nDespite the tendency in the\nWhite House to depreciate the\nserious possibilities of the Presi\ndent\u2019s illness, it was significant\nthat somebody there at one point\nsought legal advice on whether it\nwould be necessary to formally\ndelegate presidential powers to\nsomeone else. The new Attorney\nGeneral, William P. Rogers, who\nis also Mr. Nixon's closest friend\nin Washington, said that he had\nadvised the White House, after\ntalking with the doctors, that\nthere was no legal need for con\nsideration of delegating any au\nthority.\nThis brought to mind the almost\ndormant efforts, renewed in Con\ngress after each Eisenhower Ill\nness. to clarify the constitutional\nambiguity over exactly who shall\ndetermine at what point a Presi\ndent's disability requires that the\nVice President assume the presi\ndential powers and duties. Mr.\nElsenhower himself has said that\nthe need for clarification was\nurgent.\nThe Outlook\nMr Eisenhower's physicians re\nported that the President will re\nquire \"several weeks of recupera\ntion. although it became plain\nduring the week that he would\nprobably be well enough to give\nconsiderably more attention to his\njob than had first been thought.\nHe is. obviously, able to share in\nor make the decisions that must\nbe made. What is uncertain, how\never, is how much of the tiresome\nanalysis, consultation and *-rieflng\nthat are prerequisites to these de\ncisions he will be able to under\ntake.\nThe presidential agenda in\ncludes items of both global and\ndomestic importance.\nGlobal\nSince the retirement of Sir\nWinston Churchill. President Ei\nsenhower has come closest to fill\ning that articulate Englishman's\nplace as chief spokesman for the\nWestern world. With the North\nAtlantic Treaty Organization pre\nparing to meet in Paris two\nweeks from now. in what is almost\neertainly the most Important\nmeeting of the NATO Council\nsince the alliance was formed, the\nnews of the President's illness\ncame as a severe shock.\nThe importance of the Eisen\nhower prestige to the governments\nand populations of Webern Eu\nrope was never so plain as in\nthe taut responses there to the\noriginal bad news from the White\nHouse 'see stories bv Richard\nFryklund and Fred Theroux on\npage A-25i. But the news of the\nPresident's rapid recovery, plus\nthe announcement that the word\nhe would not go to Paris was\npremature, brought new optimism\nto the capitals of the NATO\npowers.\nThere Is yet no certainty that\nMi. Eisenhower will go to Paris.\nBut if his recovery continues\nalong the lines it has so far fol\nlowed, it appears likely that he\nwill make the trip.\nIn what appeared to be a mat\nter of too-hastv staff work, the\nWhite House and the State\nDepartment on Tuesday had\nannounced that \"it was to be\nassumed\u201d that the President's sud\nden illness would prevent his\nattendance at the Paris talks. But\non Friday there was some back\ntracking, and virtual admission\nthat the announcement had been\nmade without the approval of the\nPresident\u2014not too unusual a pro\ncedure under the circumstances of\nwhat appeared to be a serious ill\nness\u2014and that the Eisenhower\nrecoveiy oace had definitely re\nopened the possibility that lie\nwould eo to Paris\nNATO's Secretary-General Paul-\nHenri Spank had been as certain\nthat the President would be un\nable to make the Journey as were\nmost Americans. On Thursday Mr\nSpaak declared that, the NATO\nCouncil \"had learned with satis\nfaction'' that the American dele\ngation would be headed by Mr.\nt\nNixon. Newspapers In Paris and\nLondon were deploring the situa\ntion. expressing earnest hopes for\nthe President's recovery, and\nopenly suggesting that Mr. Eisen\nhower resign his office.\nYesterday it seemed a better\nthan-even bet that Mr. Eisen\nhower would go to Paris as he\nagreed to do after his talks with\nBritish Prime Minister Harold\nMacmillan and with Mr. Spaak\nin Washington in October.\nDomestic\nDomestic business will be much\nless demanding of Mr. Eisen\nhower's time and energy, and\nmuch of this can. and likely will,\nbe handled by Mr. Nixon.\nFinal decisions on the budget,\nnow almost ready to go to press,\nwill be required, but it is said that\nthe major decisions, such as how\nmuch to spend on the missiles\nrace, and how to get some of this\nmoney from civilian programs,\nhave already been reached, with\nonly minor details outstanding.\nAlso in the final stages is the\nPresident's economic report, due\nout in January. Barring a relapse,\nthere is no reason to believe that\nhe cannot give this as much at\ntention as is required The same\nis true of his state-of-the-Union\nmessage, due to go to Congress\nshortly after the New Year.\nHis aides are hoping that he\nwill be spared in the next few\nweeks any new domestic crises,\nsuch as the Little Rock integra\ntion dispute, which will require\ndifficult presidential decisions.\nThe lion's share of the load will\nQuite obviously be carried by Mr.\nNixon, in whom the President has\nrepeatedlv expressed confidence\nand admiration. As a natural re\nsult. the limelight that will be his\nfor the next three years will more\nfirmly cinch the Republican presi\ndential nomination for him in\n1960.\nIt may also have more immedi\nate effects. He will be charged\nwith selling the. administration's\nlegislative program to the Repub\nlican Party and to Congress. He\nwill appear more and more to be\nMr. Eisenhower s alter ego as he\nleads cabinet meetings and speaks\nout on presidential policy. Re\nporters will consider him a more\nimportant news source than here\ntofore.\nAnd as Mr. Nixon assumes an\nexpanding role m the administra\ntion. it Van be anticipated that he\nwill expect\u2014and receive\u2014a voice\nin filling top administration posi\ntions as vacancies occur.\nThe \"preparation\u201d that made\npossible Mr. Nixon's ascendancy is\nclearly one of the major con\ntributions of Mr. Eisenhower to\nthe institution of the presidency.\nMr. Nixon has been, and is. the\nfirst Vice President who is all the\ntitle Implies. His predecessors\nhave seldom been more than,\nfigureheads, presiding over the\nSenate, taking occasional \"good\nwill\u201d tours, and helping out with\nparty affairs.\nThe Missiles:\nWhy the Lag?\nWhile the President's illness\nworried a free world looking for\na new defense against a newly\npowerful Communist bloc, the\nUnited States Congress was scru\ntinizing America s defenses The\nffrst question of Senate Majority\nLeader Lyndon Johnson's Pre\npaiedness Subcommittee as Its In\nvestigation opened was \"are we\nlagging behind the Soviet Union\nIn the development of rockets and\nguided missiles, and If we are.\nwhy?\"\nThe lead-off witness Monday\nwas Dr. Edward Teller, known as\nthe \"father of the H-homb\" and\none of America's foremost nu\nclear .scientists. Dr. Teller's\ntestimony confirmed <l> that the\nUnited States is behind in the mts\u00bb\nsilcs race, and '2i that the cur\nrent rate of education of scien\ntists and engineers in the United\nStates is dangerously low. He\nurged, ax an immediate de\nfensive measure, that the Stra\ntegic Air Command promptly dis\n\nAmusements\nStart on Page A-35\nperse Its fighting strength more\nwidely, so as to increase the num\nber of necessary targets for a So\nviet attack, and that existing\nbomber fleets be reinforced as as\nsurance to the Communists that\nany missile attack would bring\nquick and deadly retaliation.\nDr. Teller was followed by Dr.\nVannevar Bush, former chief of\nthe Research and Development\nBoard and retired head of the Car\nnegie Institution. Dr. Bush,\nwhose counsels have been of ma\njor importance to American nu\nclear development since work was\nfirst begun in the Manhattan\nProject early in World War 11.\ncalled for a drastic overhauling of\nthe military missiles program He\nurged modification of the 1947\nUnification Act to end interserv\nice rivalries '\"damaging and dis\ngraceful,\" he characterized the\nservice quarrels', and the creation\nof a centralized Military Plan\nning Board, to be composed of\nmilitary men and civilians, to\ncarry out major planning, re\nlieving the Joint Chiefs of Staff\nof that function.\nRetired Lt. Gen. James H Doo\nlittle, on the second day of the\nSenate hearings, also confirmed\nthe American lag in the missile\nfield, but contended as have Pen\ntagon officials generally that the\n\"overall\" military picture still\nshowed the United States in the\nlead in military' advantage over\nthe Soviet Union. But the Rus\nsians, he warned, are fast closing\nthe gap.\nOen. Doolittle offered a military\nman's program for greater effi\nciency in the arms race: Re\norganize the Defense Department\nto de-emphasize service differ\nences, and create a single general\nstaff for the three armed services.\nTo that. Gen. Doolittle said, must\nbe added a major increase in mili\ntary spending plus a greater will\ningness of the American people to\nmake sacrifices for the common\ndefense.\nInto Production\n\"Good news.\" w as Senator John\nson's comment Wednesday when\nthe hearing was assured bv De-\nsense Secretary Neil McElroy that\nthe Thor and the Jupiter, inter\nmediate range ballistic missiles,\nhad both been ordered into pro\nduction by the Pentagon.\nMr. McElroy. who echoed mili\ntary assurances that the overall\ndefense picture was a reassuring\none, told the Senators that both\nthe Air Force Thor and the Armv\nJupiter were as yet \"not fully\ndeveloped.\" but that he and his\nmilitary advisers thought both of\nthem sufficiently well developed to\njustify their manufacture and\noperational use.\nSome testimony was heard be\nhind closed doors, and was rdfe\ncially secret However, as t.vWo\norten the case, some tncKM or tna\n\"secret\" testimony leaKed under\nthe doorsills. Senators Bridges\nRepublican of New Hampshire,\nand Symington. Democrat of Mis\nsouri. agreed that much of ths\ntestimony of Allen W. Dulles., head\nof the Central Intelligence Agency,\nand Dr. Herbert Scovllle, director\nof CIA s office of Scientific In\ntelligence. was unpleasant enough\nto shock Americans out of any\ncomplacency and \"ought to b\u00ab\ntold.\" \"A sad and shocking xtorv.\"\nsaid Senator Symington of Mr.*\nDulles' testimony.\nThe Air Force revealed Friday\nthat its intercontinental and in\ntermediate range ballistic missile\nprograms had been assigned to\nthe Strategic Air Command.\nTransfer of the programs from\nthe Atr Research and Development\nCommand is designed to speed\nthe formation of missile unit*\ntrained in the operation of un\nmanned nuclear weapons.\nIn Hnothev organizational\nchange, the White House put the\nPresident s Science Advisory Com\nmittee directly under the execu\ntive office and enlaiged lt with\nfive hew appointments tc 19 mem\nbers. This switch was described\nas one to effect a closer relation\nship between thp committee and\nthe President's newly appointed\nspecial assistant for science and\nContinued on Page A-l\u00a7\nt\nA-23","height":"28823","width":"18236"}}
